  "market_context": "CL daily price traded up into a fair value gap and closed back inside the prior candle's range, forming an upper wick. Analyst expects price to deliver lower and uses 0.5 of the wick across timeframes as the reaction level heading into the New York killzone.",
  "key_observation": "Price respecting 0.5 of the higher-timeframe wick acts as the reversal trigger, but confirmation on the lower timeframe (5M close below the level) is required before entry since reactions are not always clean.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identify on the daily that price traded up into a fair value gap and closed back inside the previous candle's range, forming a wick.",
    "Step 2: Mark 0.5 of that daily wick as the level price should respect if it is going to expand lower.",
    "Step 3: Drop to the 1H chart, observe a change in state of delivery and failure swings, and note an expansion candle lower with no upper wick.",
    "Step 4: Note price revisits the area into the New York killzone and forms an upper wick respecting the hourly candle's level.",
    "Step 5: Drop to the 5-minute chart and mark 0.5 of the hourly wick as the expected reaction zone.",
    "Step 6: Observe a close back below the marked level as added confirmation, since price first traded over it.",
    "Step 7: Enter on the confirmation close, place stop above the high, target 2R."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade reached the 2R target as price expanded lower after the confirmation close.",
  "lessons": "Reactions at 0.5 of a wick are not always clean — sometimes price overshoots before respecting the level. Waiting for additional confirmation (such as a close back below the level on the lower timeframe) allows participation even when the initial reaction is imperfect.",
